00:35:12.360 --> 00:35:14.760
So let me explain how we did it in J&J.

00:35:15.560 --> 00:35:20.600
And again, that's not maybe the right way to do it, or maybe that's the way it works

00:35:20.600 --> 00:35:23.159
for us, actually, but you can also leverage it.

00:35:23.879 --> 00:35:30.199
There is our consortium working group, our validation hub has put a guidelines document,

00:35:30.199 --> 00:35:33.320
which is really, really great to start with, actually.

00:35:34.280 --> 00:35:40.360
So we started looking at that approach, and basically, as we are juggling multiple balls,

00:35:40.360 --> 00:35:47.639
we thought it would be much better to partner with one of our vendors to see how they can

00:35:47.639 --> 00:35:52.120
help us in navigating that package validation process.

00:35:52.840 --> 00:35:59.000
So we have built a process, we have built a process with the vendor and with our IT team

00:35:59.639 --> 00:36:05.639
to have a CI-CD pipeline created and do a validation process.

00:36:05.639 --> 00:36:14.919
So as we have rolled out this R environment in a containerized fashion, we said that we

00:36:14.919 --> 00:36:21.159
are going to release two containers per year with those validated packages being in that

00:36:21.159 --> 00:36:21.879
container.

00:36:21.879 --> 00:36:26.360
So that is basically the approach we took at this point.

00:36:26.360 --> 00:36:33.399
So we work closely with one of our vendor partners to validate the packages and push

00:36:33.399 --> 00:36:40.600
that to us, and then we use our CI-CD pipeline through our JJIT to push them into a container

00:36:40.600 --> 00:36:42.600
release for that.

